  "prompt": "Can I claim HRA during ITR Filing?",
  "response": "Yes, you can claim House Rent Allowance (HRA) during ITR filing if you meet certain conditions. Here's a breakdown of how it works and the requirements:\n\n**What is HRA?**\n\nHRA is a part of your salary that your employer provides to help you pay for your rental accommodation. It's designed to reduce your tax liability.\n\n**Eligibility to Claim HRA:**\n\n*   **You must be a salaried individual:** HRA is specifically for salaried employees.\n*   **HRA must be a part of your salary package:**  Your salary slip should explicitly show an HRA component.\n*   **You must be paying rent:**  You need to be actually paying rent for a residential accommodation.  You can't claim HRA if you live in your own house (or a house owned by your spouse or children, and you don't pay rent).\n*   **The rented property must be occupied by you:** You must be residing in the rented property.\n\n**How to Calculate the HRA Exemption:**\n\nThe Income Tax Act provides for an exemption of the *least* of the following three amounts:\n\n1.  **Actual HRA received from your employer.**\n2.  **50% of your salary (Basic + DA) if you live in a metro city (Delhi, Mumbai, Kolkata, Chennai). 40% of your salary (Basic + DA) if you live in a non-metro city.**\n3.  **Actual rent paid minus 10% of your salary (Basic + DA).**\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Salary for HRA Calculation:** For HRA calculations, \"Salary\" usually refers to your Basic Salary plus Dearness Allowance (DA), if any. It *does not* include other allowances or perquisites.\n*   **Rent Receipts:**  You *must* have rent receipts to claim HRA. If your annual rent payment exceeds \u20b91,00,000, you are *required* to provide the landlord's name, address, and PAN (Permanent Account Number). Failure to provide this information can lead to your HRA claim being disallowed.\n*   **Living with Parents:**  You *can* claim HRA if you pay rent to your parents, provided the following conditions are met:\n    *   You have a valid rental agreement with your parents.\n    *   You are actually paying rent to your parents (through bank transfer is ideal, for proof).\n    *   Your parents declare this rental income in their Income Tax Return.\n    *   Your parents must be the actual owners of the property.\n*   **Living with Spouse:** You cannot claim HRA if you pay rent to your spouse. The property is essentially considered to be owned by both of you.\n*   **Simultaneous HRA and Home Loan Benefits:** You *can* claim both HRA and home loan interest deduction benefits if you live in a rented accommodation in one city and own a house in another city (e.g., you work in Mumbai and have a home loan for a property in your hometown).  However, you will need to provide valid reasons for living in rented accommodation despite owning a house (e.g., employment is in a different city).\n*   **Form 16:** Your Form 16 (issued by your employer) will usually show the amount of HRA you received and the amount of HRA exemption claimed (if any).\n*   **Choosing between HRA and Section 80GG (for self-employed):**  If you are self-employed or do not receive HRA as part of your salary, you may be eligible to claim a deduction under Section 80GG of the Income Tax Act for rent paid.  You *cannot* claim both HRA and Section 80GG. Section 80GG has more restrictive conditions and usually results in a smaller deduction compared to HRA.\n*   **Documentation:** Keep all relevant documents (rent receipts, rental agreement, landlord's PAN card if applicable) handy for verification purposes. The Income Tax Department may ask for these documents during scrutiny.\n\n**How to Claim HRA While Filing ITR:**\n\n1.  **Go to the Income Tax Department's e-filing portal:**  (incometax.gov.in)\n2.  **Choose the appropriate ITR form:**  This will depend on your income sources. Most salaried individuals use ITR-1 or ITR-2.\n3.  **Fill out the required information:**  Under the \"Income from Salary\" section, you will find a field to enter the amount of HRA received and the amount of HRA exemption you are claiming.  The ITR form will likely guide you through the calculation.  You will need the details from your Form 16 and your rent receipts.\n4.  **Submit your ITR:**  After filling out all the required information and verifying it, submit your ITR online.\n\n**Important Note:** Tax laws and regulations can change. It's always best to consult with a qualified tax advisor or refer to the latest official publications from the Income Tax Department for the most up-to-date information. Don't rely solely on this information; it's for general guidance only. Mistakes in your tax filing can lead to penalties and scrutiny.\n",
